    <div class='section-content js-trigger'>
			<p class='section-intro'>We generally follow the AP Style Guide and The Elements of Style. Below are a few key points from these to pay close attention to, as well as a few points where we vary from their guidelines to better form our own brand.</p>
	
			<h2 id="abbreviations">Abbreviations and Acronyms</h2>
				<ul>
					<li>"Do not take shortcuts at the cost of clarity." <em>The Elements of Style</em></li>
					<li>Start out using the full name. After meaning is understood, use the abbreviation. If it is a commonly known acronym or abbreviation, use the shortened form (e.g., URL, sync, TBD, etc.).</li>
					<li>Etc., e.g., and i.e.</li>
					<ul>
						<li>Use them! Just remember the appropriate punctuation: etc. is <em>always</em> followed by a period, as are each letter in e.g. and i.e.</li>
						<li>Don't forget the comma after the last period if it's at the beginning or middle of a sentence.</li>
						<li>Tip for these: E.g., means <em>for example</em>. I.e., means <em>in other words</em>. Read the sentence with these included if you're trying to decide which to use, you'll know what sounds correct.</li>
					</ul>		
				</ul>	
		
			<h2 id="capitalization">Capitalization</h2>
				<ul>
					<li><strong>Do:</strong> names of Ahalogy tools and technology</li>
						<ul>
							<li>[Ahalogy] Content Network</li>
							<li>Ahalogy Mobile</li>
							<li>Smart Stacks</li>
						</ul>	
					<li><strong>Do:</strong> names of Pinterest tools and technology</li>
						<ul>
							<li>Smart Feed</li>
							<li>Promoted Pins</li>
						</ul>	
					<li><strong>Don't:</strong> job titles that aren't modifiers, random words that aren't proper nouns, or actions that our tools complete</li>
						<ul>
							<li>schedule</li>
							<li>pin</li>
							<li>optimize</li>
							<li>content partnership manager</li>
							<li>client director</li>
						</ul>	
				</ul>	
	
			<h2 id="commas">Commas</h2>
				<ul>
					<li>Serial, or "Oxford" commas&mdash;use them! We aren't animals. E.g., I like cookies, cupcakes, and chocolate.  Not: I like cookies, cupcakes and chocolate.</li>
					<li>Take a sensical approach in your use of commas. Read the sentence out loud. If you are naturally taking a breath in a sentence, insert a comma.</li>
					<li>Enclose parenthetic expressions in commas.</li>
				</ul>	
	
			<h2 id="dashes">Dashes and Hyphens</h2>
				<ul>
					<li>Use em dashes&mdash;sans spaces&mdash;to set off a parenthetical statement when looking for something more emphatic than commas. The mac keystroke is: option + shift + hyphen.</li> 
					<li>En dashes are to be used for ranges of numbers, dates, or times. The mac keystroke is: option + hyphen. (e.g., I will be ready in 5&ndash;10 minutes.)</li>
					<li>Hyphens are used for compound modifiers before nouns. (e.g., This is our bi-weekly meeting to discuss progress.)</li>
					<li>Since these each have specific use cases and meanings, avoid using any of in place of one another.</li>
				</ul>	
	
			<h2 id="dates">Dates</h2>
				<ul>
					<li>Years: Only use apostrophes when abbreviating years or decades, to replace the omitted numbers.</li>
					<li>Spell out the month unless it is used with a date. When used with a date, abbreviate only the following months: <em>Jan., Feb., Aug., Sept., Oct., Nov. and Dec.</em></li> 
					<li>Do not use <em>st, nd, rd, or th.</em> <s>Jan. 24th.</s> Jan. 24. Or; Jan. 24, 2015.</li>
				</ul>
	
			<h2 id="ellipsis">Ellipsis</h2>
				<ul>
					<li>Use to indicate you've omitted one or more words from a quote.</li>
					<li>An ellipsis should be constructed with three periods and a space on each side.</li>
					<li>Never begin a sentence with an ellipsis, even if you're not using the first word(s) of the original quote.</li>
					<li>Never use ellipsis in a title or header of a document, slide in a deck, or email.</li>
				</ul>
	
			<h2 id="emphasis">Emphasis</h2>
				<ul>
					<li>Use italics, bold, and underline when fitting. Never in any combination, <em><u>it</u></em> <strong>looks <u>weird</u></strong>.</li>
					<li>Always use italics for titles of works.</li>
					<li>Do not use caps for emphasis. NO NEED TO YELL AT ANYONE&mdash;WE DON'T SELL USED CARS HERE.</li>
					<li>Colors can be used to emphasize in decks, pdf documents, and newsletters. Never in personal email. Be sure to follow our visual identity for the right colors.</li>

				</ul>
	
			<h2 id="exclamation">Exclamation Points</h2>
				<ul>
					<li>Do not use to emphasize a simple statement.</li> 
					<li>Exclamations should be cherished and used only as a literary high five.</li>
					<li>Do not use more than one in any support or guide content, two in an email, or four in a blog post.</li>
					<li>Never use in a white paper or case study.</li>
				</ul>
	
			<h2 id="lists">Lists</h2>
				<ul>
					<li>Always number items that should be in a certain order, don't use numbers when order doesn't matter.</li>
				</ul>
	
			<h2 id="numbers">Numbers</h2>
				<ul>
					<li>Spell out numbers less than 10.</li>
					<li>Spell out ordinal numbers first through ninth: first, second, third, fourth, fifth, sixth, etc.</li>
				</ul>
	
			<h2 id="quotes">Quotes</h2>
				<ul>
					<li>Periods and commas always go inside the quotation marks.</li>
					<li>Do not use to emphasize a word or phrase.</li>
				</ul>
	
			<h2 id="times">Times</h2>
				<ul>
					<li>Zones (depending on whether or not daylight savings time applies): EST, EDT, PST, PDT, CST, CDT, MST, MDT</li>
				</ul>
	
			<h2 id="widows">Widows and Orphans</h2>
				<ul>
					<li>"Orphans have no past, and widows have no future."</li>
					<li>Words or short lines at the beginning or end of a paragraph, which are left dangling at the top or bottom of a column, separated from the rest of the paragraph.</li>
					<li>Avoid these as to keep clean, purposeful looking prose.</li>
				</ul>
    </div>
