          <h3>Pin Allotment</h3><p>The allocation of your pins between your self-published content and those from the Content Network. This allows Ahalogy's tools know how many of each type you'd like to be posted per day. We recommend a pretty even balance.</p>
   
          <h3>Pin Score</h3><p>A Pin Score is attached to each pin in the Content Network. It's a 0-100 ranking that takes into account the amount of repins and click-throughs a piece of content is getting compared to the number of followers that partner has.</p>
  
          <h3>Promoted Pin</h3><p>A content creator or brand can choose to pay to promote a certain Pin as part of a campaign. The promoter can target the Pin to certain audiences based on different parameters like gender, geography, interests, etc.</p>
   
          <h3>reach</h3><p>The number or scale of people who saw a Pin. Correlated with impressions, but not identical.</p>
   
         <h3>repin (verb), repinned</h3><p>Choosing to save and share a Pin that someone else has posted.</p>
  
          <h3>Rich Pin</h3><p>Rich Pins use meta data to pull in more information on specific Pins, allowing them to stand out in the feed. There are seven types: product, recipe, movie, article, place, and app. Each type pulls in different information, for example: a Recipe Pin might pull in the list of ingredients needed, so the Pinner can see what it encompases before clicking through. An App Pin allows you to download the app right from the Pin.</p>
 
